Welcome to the Cheetah Team workspace. Use this to share design proposals and details, results of technical analyses, etc.

## Featured Pages

## Recently Updated

> Info: NEED INSPIRATION?Check out our guide on building better documentation to learn best practices for creating and organizing documents in Confluence.

## Accessing the WordPress Help CMS

The WordPress Help CMS can be accessed at:
[https://help.inventanalytics.com/wp-admin/](https://help.inventanalytics.com/wp-admin/)

> ⚠️ VPN connection is required to access this page. Make sure you are connected to the company VPN before proceeding.

### Requesting Access

Before logging in, users must request the WordPress Editor role by posting in the ask-cheetah Slack channel.

Once the role is assigned:

- Login credentials (username and temporary password) will be sent via email.
- Users can log in using the link above.

### Navigating to All Pages

After logging in, follow these steps:

1. Click Pages from the left-hand menu
2. Open All Pages to see the full list of help pages.
3. Click Add New to create a new help page, or select an existing report by clicking its title to edit.

The image below highlights these steps visually for quick reference.

All Pages

## Creating or Editing Help Page

Creating or Editing Help Page

### Page Title & Permalink

- Enter the page title at the top of the page.
- The permalink (URL) is automatically generated from the title and the last part of permalink represents the slug of the documentation. [You can see the slug formatting rules in the next section]
- You can edit the slug using the Edit button next to the permalink, however this is strongly discouraged for existing documentation, as the URL may already be referenced or used elsewhere.
- Check the Useful Tips section for detailed information.

### Content

If you need to link to another help page within a help page, you can use the URL of that page as a hyperlink anchor.

### Categories

- Select at least one category from the Categories panel on the right.
- Categories are required to:Maintain content order.Improve discoverability.Simplify long-term management.

### Publishing

metadata.title: WordPress Guide: Help Pages & Documentation CMS

content:
red to:Maintain content order.Improve discoverability.Simplify long-term management.

### Publishing

- Once the content is ready, click Publish to make the page live.
- You may also use Save Draft if the page is not ready yet.

---

## Slug Formatting Rules (Global & Customer-Specific)

In report help pages, the Tableau Cloud workbook name is mapped to the corresponding UI screens.
When creating documentation for a new report:

- Use the Tableau Cloud workbook name as the slug.
- Select the appropriate product category.

### Global Documentation

- A slug in the format sample-help-slug is considered global and may be shared across multiple customers. Identifying the correct slug is explained in the Useful Tips section at the end of the document.

> Warning: Global documentation must not be modified for customer-specific requirements.

### Customer-Specific Documentation

metadata.title: WordPress Guide: Help Pages & Documentation CMS

content:
tation must not be modified for customer-specific requirements.

### Customer-Specific Documentation

- Selecting a category alone is not sufficient for customer-specific help pages.
- Always clone the global page and create a separate customer-specific document.
- If a customer-specific help page exists, it will be displayed; otherwise, the default (global) page will be used.
- Customer-specific slugs must follow this format(the list of customer group tags is provided at the end of this document):

```
customer-key-sample-help-slug
```

Duplication of a document

---

## Language Tabs (Managing Multilingual Content)

Language Tabs

When updating customer-specific documentation or creating new help pages, language tabs on the Add / Update Page screen allow content to be customized by language.

Language-specific content behaves as follows:

metadata.title: WordPress Guide: Help Pages & Documentation CMS

content:
ge screen allow content to be customized by language.

Language-specific content behaves as follows:

- The Invent UI displays help content based on the user’s selected language. If content exists for that language (for example, Deutsch), it is shown; otherwise, the system defaults to English.
- For customer-specific pages requiring multiple languages, content should be added under each relevant language tab.

This structure ensures that a single help page can be managed globally, customer-specifically, and in multiple languages when needed.

---

### Using Quick Edit

- Quick Edit allows updating title, slug, categories, and status without opening the full editor.

Using Quick Edit

content:
The Invent 2.0 UI strives to maximize reusability of components. A common element that will be used in many situations is a filter pane, which enables powerful and flexible selection of data for display in tables and graphs. A first version of this pane is already being used in the Allocation Approval application for Academy Sports. From early experience with that design, we have identified a number of areas for improvement. This document describes a proposed new version of the filtering pane that addresses those issues. The improvements fall into three categories:

- Visual parsimony: only display information needed to describe the filters being applied
- Ease of Use: reduce the number of steps involved in managing filters
- UI responsiveness: filter updates should appear to be instantaneous to the user

Proposed changes for each area follow.

In the current design, there are two basic sets of filters; one set is related to products, and the other is related to locations. Each set consists of drop down boxes for each attribute that can be filtered. For products, that includes hierarchical attributes such as Division, Department, Class, Subclass, etc., as well as others like Vendor, Season Code, etc. Similarly, for locations there are also both hierarchical and non-hierarchical attributes. The problem is that all of these drop-down boxes take up a lot of vertical space, and only a small number are ever used concurrently. An alternative is to have a drop down box that lists the available attributes that can be used for filtering; when you choose one of those elements, a new drop down box appears that can be used to select values of that attribute. This approach has already been largely implemented to deal with user-defined attributes; here we propose to use it for all attributes.

- it supports an unlimited number of attributes without taking up page real estate,
- the filter attributes being used are clearly labeled (under the current design, the attribute’s label is not displayed if values of that attribute have been selected)
- you only see attributes and related values that are being used to filter the data
- it should be more responsive to filter changes. When you choose attribute values, the only updates that need to occur are to the list of available values for the attributes that have already been selected. For example, currently, if you choose one department, then the class, subclass, style, and buyer attribute drop downs all get refreshed to show only values valid for that department. Under the new approach, in the example shown above, only the Season Code drop down box would be refreshed. If you then decide to include another filter attribute, such as subclass, its list of valid values would be built based on the already specified filter values.

h as subclass, its list of valid values would be built based on the already specified filter values.

The one disadvantage of this approach is that there is one extra step in choosing filter values, because you must first choose the filter element, then the values. One other thing to note is that we will need to have a way to “de-select” an attribute and have its drop-down box removed.

## Ease of Use

The current design includes the ability to create, save, modify, and delete your own custom filters.  The process for creating and saving filters needs to be streamlined.

Saved Filters Current Flow

To create a filter you must do the following:

needs to be streamlined.

Saved Filters Current Flow

To create a filter you must do the following:

1. If you have already selected a saved filter, you must first de-select it in the custom filter drop down box; this will cause a Save button to appear.
2. Select filter elements and related values
3. Click on Save; this will cause it to prompt you for a filter name
4. Enter a name for the filter; if you want to make it the default filter, click on the associated check box
5. Click on Confirm to save the new filter

To update an existing saved filter, you currently do the following:

1. Select the saved filter
2. Change the selected filter elements and values
3. Click on Update

Saved Filters New Flow

The proposed new approach for creating or updating a saved filter requires that there be two buttons visible at all times: Save and Save As. The flow would be:

filter requires that there be two buttons visible at all times: Save and Save As. The flow would be:

1. Select filter elements and related values
2. If you had previously selected a saved filter, and want to update it, select Save
3. To create a new filter, select Save As; this will cause it to prompt you for a filter name Enter a name for the filter; if you want to make it the default filter, click on the associated check boxClick on Confirm to save the new filter

Note that if you have not selected a saved filter, the Savebutton will be disabled.

## UI Responsiveness

Updates to filters have to be very fast - as close to instantaneous as possible. A delay of more than one second when choosing attributes and values will be irritating to users. Currently, when updating the values for a hierarchical attribute, there are two sources of delay:

s. Currently, when updating the values for a hierarchical attribute, there are two sources of delay:

- After selecting a value to include, you have to wait about 2 seconds before the UI does anything
- Once it starts updating the filters, it takes about 2 more seconds

The first delay is because it is waiting to see if you are done making changes before it initiates the updating of the drop-down lists for all other attributes. If you choose a second value within the 2 second window, it appears that it resets the timer and waits another 2 seconds. This delay doesn’t occur for “non-hierarchical” attributes, even though selecting values for those should affect the available choices for many of the other drop-downs.

rs should exported to somewhere, to be discussed and agreed between the parts, for the file delivery. The Edit Range enables the user to edit multiple cells at once with a formula. The user should be asked which metric he would like to lock and between which dates and for how long. Also, the user should be able to Unlock the already locked cells. ## Library Selection to Wrap

When choosing a UI library to set a base to create custom UI library, there are few major points to be considered.

- Comprehensiveness, UI Library should have as many as different component options.
- Documentation, it should include detailed explanations and examples for customization.
- Users, active users and multitude of discussions on the web to provide support.
- Availability, the library package should be stable and open source.
- Customizability, components should be highly flexible in order to shape them into a custom UI library components.

The libraries we’ve examined are all successfull and well designed libraries but it when compared to one another, we’ve found the following results:

and well designed libraries but it when compared to one another, we’ve found the following results:

*Semantic UI*, not very comprehensive.
*Material UI,* small scope of documentation, high number of users and availability.
*React Admin*, requires us to make extra changes in backend as well.
*Vechai UI,* not very comprehensive and few documentation.
*PrimeReact,* good documentation and comprehensiveness.
*Kendo UI*, has good grid components that we can use but it’s not open source and free.

Conclusion:Antd is highly customizable, second most used UI library with very good documentations and vast number of components. We’ve decided to move forward with it.

- Creating new users for Invent Analytics is done by the cheetah team only. You can create users for the client via Admin → User Management → Create New User tab.
- After a user is created, the system sends a password for the first entry. If this password is not used within a week, it deactivates. Therefore, make sure newly created users enter the system and create their own passwords as soon as possible.
- You can view the activities of users via Admin → User Audit page. This page provides the information about when a user was created, what were the last login and request dates and whether a user is enabled or not.
- You can activate MFA for individual users if requested by the client. Contact cheetah for activation.
- Make sure all members of the project team have access to the website as Markdown Invent Admin role. You can change the permissions for Invent users via Admin → User Management → Update & Delete User tab.

can change the permissions for Invent users via Admin → User Management → Update & Delete User tab.
- You can change the permissions for client users via Admin → User Management → Update & Delete User tab. For the markdown product, there are 4 different roles. Markdown Client AdminMarkdown Client ExecutiveMarkdown Client ReporterMarkdown Invent Admin
- Specifications for these roles can change for each customer, and should be specified by the project manager at the beginning of the project. Detailed descriptions for these roles in existing customers can be found here.
- In addition to these roles, you can limit the categories that are seen and affected by each user via user interface (Admin → User Management | Restrictions). For example, if there are two users with the same Markdown Client Reporter permission, you can limit the categories seen and affected by one to Shoes and other to T-shirts.

er permission, you can limit the categories seen and affected by one to Shoes and other to T-shirts.
- If you want users to be managed and controlled by the client, you can grant access to User Management capability for the Markdown Client Admin role.

# Single Sign-On (SSO) Overview

Single Sign-On (SSO) allows users to access Invent UI with their existing corporate credentials instead of managing separate usernames and passwords. Authentication is handled through AWS Cognito, integrated with your Identity Provider (IdP) via SAML 2.0.

Supported IdPs: Azure Active Directory, Google Workspace, Okta, or any SAML 2.0 provider.

---

## Benefits

- Improved security – No local password storage.
- Simplified user lifecycle – Disabling an employee in the IdP automatically removes Invent access.
- Convenience – No need for extra credentials.

noteFallback – If SSO is not configured, customers must assign administrators to regularly review and disable unused accounts.

Fallback – If SSO is not configured, customers must assign administrators to regularly review and disable unused accounts.

---

## Modes

customers must assign administrators to regularly review and disable unused accounts.

---

## Modes

- Forced SSO → All users must log in via SSO (password login disabled).
- Optional SSO → Users may log in via SSO or password. Password login can be protected with MFA.

---

# User Lifecycle (Onboarding & Deprovisioning)

- Onboarding – When a user is assigned to the app in the IdP and logs in for the first time, Cognito performs Just-in-Time (JIT) provisioning and creates their Invent account.
- Update – User attributes refresh on every login.
- Deprovisioning – Removing the assignment in the IdP blocks access. Sessions expire automatically based on TTL.
- SCIM – Not supported. AWS Cognito does not expose SCIM endpoints. Provisioning is handled solely through SAML + JIT.

---

# Attribute Mapping

| Attribute | Required | Purpose |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Email | Yes | Primary identifier for account match |
| custom:role | No | Enables automatic role assignment |

es | Primary identifier for account match |
| custom:role | No | Enables automatic role assignment |

- If custom:role is provided, Invent maps it to predefined roles in the Database.
- Customers must share a role mapping CSV so Invent can configure associations.
- Environment-specific role values (for example, super_user for Production and super_user_uat for UAT) must also be included. This ensures users receive the correct access for each environment, since Invent operates a single Cognito pool across all customers and environments.
- Without it, roles must be managed manually in Invent.

---

# Role Mapping Examples

| Incoming Role | Invent Roles Assigned |
| --- | --- |
| TRN Super User | Transfer Client Admin, Transfer Client User, Transfer Report User |
| TRN Super User UAT | Same roles, UAT only |
| RPL Admin | Replenishment Client Admin |
| All Admin | Transfer + Markdown + Replenishment C Admin |

# Setup Requirements

### Customer → Invent

Provide IdP metadata:

- Metadata URL (preferred for auto-updates), or
- Metadata XML file

### Invent → Customer

Invent provides:

- Cognito Pool ID (SP Entity ID) → Unique identifier of Invent’s SAML service provider. A single Cognito pool is used for all customers, with role-based access managed internally.
- ACS (Assertion Consumer Service) / Reply URL → Endpoint that receives the SAML assertion after authentication.

# IdP Configuration (Customer Side)

1. Entity ID → Set to Cognito Pool ID
2. ACS URL → Set to Consumer Service URL
3. User Attributes → Email (mandatory), Role (optional)
4. Certificates → IdP must include public signing certificate in metadata
5. User Assignment → Assign users/groups explicitly in the IdP

metadata.title: How to upload a csv to Google Big Query (GBQ)?

content:
## Summary

The Cheetah Target Parameter screen allows us to manage numeric values for a parameter at the product, store, and pair levels. Stored parameter values can be written in CSV format to any desired object storage (AWS S3 or Azure Blob) with an API request.

## Requirements

### Product & Store Master Data

To use this screen, product, and store master data are required. If the customer uses the Maps Transfer product, the data is acquired by Cheetah through a temporary ETL solution. Otherwise, the data needs to be delivered to Cheetah Services. The following methods can be used:

- The data can be delivered to Cheetah Services by writing a Rocks Opal extension.
- Manual implementation can be used for data delivery.

### Manuel Implementation

Product and Store master data should be written in the following format to an AWS S3 or Azure Blob storage (preferably a customer datastore), and the schema should be as follows:

Product Schema

Blob storage (preferably a customer datastore), and the schema should be as follows:

Product Schema

| Column Name | Data Type | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| product_id | INTEGER | PK |
| product_code | STRING | PK |
| product_description | STRING |  |
| product_hierarchy_n_code | STRING | n = 1 to 8 |
| product_hierarchy_n_description | STRING | n = 1 to 8 |
| product_descriptive_n | STRING | n = 1 to 20 |
| brand | STRING |  |
| size_code | STRING |  |
| color_code | STRING |  |
| model_code | STRING |  |
| option_code | STRING |  |
| season_code | STRING |  |
| season_description | STRING |  |
| season_type | STRING |  |
| season_year | INTEGER |  |

Store Schema

son_description | STRING |  |
| season_type | STRING |  |
| season_year | INTEGER |  |

Store Schema

| Column Name | Data Type | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| store_id | INTEGER | PK |
| store_code | STRING | PK |
| store_description | STRING |  |
| location_hierarchy_n_code | STRING | n = 1 to 5 |
| location_hierarchy_n_description | STRING | n = 1 to 5 |
| location_descriptive_n | STRING | n = 1 to 20 |
| channel_type | STRING |  |
| building_type | STRING |  |
| brand_type | STRING |  |
| selling_type | STRING |  |
| store_size | DECIMAL |  |
| is_blocked | INTEGER |  |

The directory structure for the prepared CSV files should be as follows:

```
any_prefix/products/default/any_filename_1.csv
any_prefix/stores/default/any_filename_1.csv
```

```
any_prefix/products/default/any_filename_1.csv
any_prefix/stores/default/any_filename_1.csv
```

Multiple CSV files can be stored within the default directory, and all of them should have a CSV header row. It is essential to ensure that there are no CSV files other than the relevant data in the directory, as all CSV files in the directory will be read.

The CSV data can be imported using the Cheetah API.

[https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/cheetah/shu/shu-proxy-gateway/-/blob/dev/doc/swagger.yaml](https://gitlab.com/invent-analytics/cheetah/shu/shu-proxy-gateway/-/blob/dev/doc/swagger.yaml)

### How to use Cheetah APIs

To use the Cheetah REST API, you must first generate an access token. This access token is used to authenticate the identity of the requester in each API request, and the access token is added to the HTTP request header with the "Authorization" key.

### How to obtain an access token

is added to the HTTP request header with the "Authorization" key.

### How to obtain an access token

Cheetah uses the AWS Cognito service for authentication. This service is implemented using the OAuth2 protocol, and an access token can be obtained by making a client credentials grant type request. The client_id and client_secret information required for this request is kept a secret for each customer. These secrets are stored using AWS Secret Manager and Azure KeyVault.

- CSS Modules

> Info: While working locally, execute the ‘npm run build' and 'npm pack' commands for the Cub UI project. Subsequently, install the generated .tgz file in the Cheetah UI project using the path as  like 'npm i ../cub/cub-0.0.1.tgz’

Steps:

1. Build Set Up

While the 'src' folder in the project serves as a demonstration area, the core library resides in a separate folder named 'lib.'

Our primary entry point is 'main.ts' within the 'lib' directory. Upon installing our library, all components will be exported from this location.

#### Vite Library Mode (For further information )

#### Vite lib Mode (For further information )

At this time, if you build the project with npm run build Vite will transpile the code inside ‘src’ to the dist folder. This is default Vite behavior.

n build Vite will transpile the code inside ‘src’ to the dist folder. This is default Vite behavior.

For now you will use the demo page for development purposes only. So there is no need to transpile this part of the project yet. Instead you want to transpile and ship the code inside of `lib`.

This is where Vite's *Library Mode* comes into play. It was designed specifically for building/transpiling libraries. To activate this mode, simply specify your library entry point in vite.config.ts.

In vite.config.ts we add;

```
lib: {
  entry: resolve(__dirname, 'lib/main.ts'),
  formats: ['es'],
  fileName: (format) => `cub.${format}.ts`,
},
```

> Info: The default formats are 'es' and 'umd'. For your component library 'es' is all you need. This also removes the necessity for adding the name property.

> Info: If your Typescript linter complains about 'path' and __dirname just install the types for node: npm i @types/node -D

#### Adding Typescript to library mode

#### Adding Typescript to library mode

The Vite-generated tsconfig.json file initially includes only the 'src' folder. To enable TypeScript for the 'lib' folder you've created, simply add it to the TypeScript configuration file as follows

```js
"include": ["src", "lib"],
```

Later, for testing the library on the demo page, components will be imported directly from the 'dist' folder. To avoid TypeScript errors when importing components that haven't been built yet, it's necessary to exclude the 'src' folder when building the library.

One way to do this is to create a separate configuration file for building and extend `tsconfig.json`:

```
 +┣ 📜tsconfig-build.json
```

The only difference between the default configuration and the build configuration is that for building you only have `lib` included instead of `lib` and `src`.

`📜tsconfig-build.json`

```
{
  "extends": "./tsconfig.json",
  "include": ["lib"]
}
```

and `src`.

`📜tsconfig-build.json`

```
{
  "extends": "./tsconfig.json",
  "include": ["lib"]
}
```

To use `tsconfig-build.json` for building you need to pass the configuration file to `tsc` in the build script in your package.json:

```
"build": "tsc --p ./tsconfig-build.json && vite build",
```

Finally, remember to copy the 'vite-env.d.ts' file from 'src' to 'lib.' This step is crucial because without this file, TypeScript will miss certain type definitions provided by Vite during the build process, especially since we no longer include 'src'.

Now when we run

```
npm run build
```

we will see

```
 📂dist
  ┣ 📜cub.js
  ┗ 📜vite.svg
```

> Info: The name of the output file is identical with the “name” property in your package.json per default. This can be changed in the Vite config (build.lib.fileName) but we will do something else about this later.

n be changed in the Vite config (build.lib.fileName) but we will do something else about this later.

The file `vite.svg` is in your `dist` folder because Vite copies all files from the `public` directory to the output folder. Let's disable this [behavior](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/75276160/why-is-the-file-vite-svg-in-the-dist-folder-when-building-with-vite-library):

```
+  copyPublicDir: false,
```

As this is a Typescript library you also want to ship type definitions with your package. Fortunately there is a Vite plugin that does exactly this: [vite-plugin-dts](https://github.com/qmhc/vite-plugin-dts)

Per default `dts` will generate types for both `src` and `lib` because both folders are included in the project's `.tsconfig`. This is why we need to pass one configuration parameter: `include: ['lib']`.

1. Add Css Modules

As mentioned in the beginning, this library will use [CSS modules](https://github.com/css-modules/css-modules) to style the components.

CSS modules are supported by Vite per default. All you have to do is to create CSS files that end with `.module.css`.

#### Add your style to library

After transpiling your library you will notice that there is a new file in your distribution folder:

But there are two issues with this file:

1. You need to manually import the file in the consuming application.
2. It is one file that contains all styles for all components.

#### Import the CSS

CSS files just can't easily be imported in JavaScript. Therefore, the CSS file is generated separately, allowing the library user to decide how to handle the file.

But what if we were to assume that the application using the library has a bundler configuration that can handle CSS imports?

sume that the application using the library has a bundler configuration that can handle CSS imports?

For this to work, the transpiled JavaScript bundle must contain an import statement for the CSS file. We are going to use yet another Vite plugin ([vite-plugin-lib-inject-css](https://github.com/emosheeep/fe-tools/tree/master/packages/vite-plugin-lib-inject-css)) that does exactly what we need with zero configuration.

```
npm i vite-plugin-lib-inject-css -D
```

```
// vite.config.ts
+import { libInjectCss } from 'vite-plugin-lib-inject-css'
…
  plugins: [
    react(),
+   libInjectCss(),
    dts({ include: ['lib'] })
  ],
```

Build the library and take a look at the top of your bundled JavaScript file (`dist/my-component-library.js`):

```
// dist/my-component-library.js
import "./main.css";
…
```

le (`dist/my-component-library.js`):

```
// dist/my-component-library.js
import "./main.css";
…
```

> Info: You may notice that the CSS filename has changed from style.css to main.css. This change occurs because the plugin generates a separate CSS file for each chunk, and in this case the name of the chunk comes from the filename of the entry file.

#### Split up the CSS

But there's still the second problem: when you import something from your library, `main.css` is also imported and all the CSS styles end up in your application bundle. Even if you only import the button.

The `libInjectCSS` plugin generates a separate CSS file for each chunk and includes an import statement at the beginning of each chunk's output file.

So if you split up the JavaScript code, you end up having separate CSS files that only get imported when the according JavaScript files are imported.

p having separate CSS files that only get imported when the according JavaScript files are imported.

One way of doing this would be to turn every file into an Rollup entry point. And, it couldn't be better, there is a recommended way of doing this right in the [Rollup documentation](https://rollupjs.org/configuration-options/#input):

> 📘 If you want to convert a set of files to another format while maintaining the file structure and export signatures, the recommended way—instead of using output.preserveModules that may tree-shake exports as well as emit virtual files created by plugins—is to turn every file into an entry point.

So let's add this to your configuration.

First install `glob` as it will be required:

```
npm i glob -D
```

Then change your Vite config to this:

install `glob` as it will be required:

```
npm i glob -D
```

Then change your Vite config to this:

```js
// vite.config.ts
-import { resolve } from 'path'
+import { extname, relative, resolve } from 'path'
+import { fileURLToPath } from 'node:url'
+import { glob } from 'glob'
…
    rollupOptions: {
      external: ['react', 'react/jsx-runtime'],
+  input: Object.fromEntries(
+        // https://rollupjs.org/configuration-options/#input
+        glob.sync('lib//*.{ts,tsx}').map(file => [
+          // 1. The name of the entry point
+          // lib/nested/foo.js becomes nested/foo
+          relative(
+            'lib',
+            file.slice(0, file.length - extname(file).length)
+          ),
+          // 2. The absolute path to the entry file
+          // lib/nested/foo.ts becomes /project/lib/nested/foo.ts
+          fileURLToPath(new URL(file, import.meta.url))
+        ])
+      ),
    }
…
```

lib` alongside with their type definitions. And the CSS files are inside a new folder called assets.

Notice that the name of the main file has changed from "my-component-library.js" to "main.js". That's great!

1. Last Steps

#### Main file

Every npm package has a primary entry point, per default this file is `index.js` in the root of the package.

Your library's primary entry point is now located at `dist/main.js`, so this needs to be set in your `package.json`. The same applies to the type's entry point: `dist/main.d.ts`

#### Define the files to publish

You should also define which files should be packed into your distributed package.

```
// package.json
  …
  "main": "dist/main.js",
  "types": "dist/main.d.ts",
+ "files": [
+   "dist"
+ ],
  …
```

> Info: Certain files like package.json or README are always included, regardless of settings: Read the docs

#### Dependencies

package.json or README are always included, regardless of settings: Read the docs

#### Dependencies

Now take a look at your `dependencies`: right now there should be only two `react` and `react-dom` and a couple of `devDependencies`.

You can move those two to the `devDepedencies` as well. And additionally add them as `peerDependencies` so the consuming application is aware that it must have React installed to use this package.

```
// package.json
- "dependencies": {
+ "peerDependencies": {
    "react": "^18.2.0",
    "react-dom": "^18.2.0"
  },
  "devDependencies": {
+   "react": "^18.2.0",
+   "react-dom": "^18.2.0",
    …
  }
```

> Info: See this StackOverflow answer to learn more about the different types of dependencies: Link

#### Side effects

To prevent the CSS files from being accidentally removed by the consumer's tree-shaking efforts, you should also specify the generated CSS as side effects:

```
+ "sideEffects": [
+   "/*.css"
+ ],
```

should also specify the generated CSS as side effects:

```
+ "sideEffects": [
+   "/*.css"
+ ],
```

#### Ensure that the package is built

You can use the special lifecycle script `prepublishOnly` to guarantee that your changes are always built before the package is published:

```
// package.json
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "vite",
    "build": "tsc && vite build",
    …
+   "prepublishOnly": "npm run build"
  },
```

3 - Phantom Stock SSO

Since the user base in the Phantom Stock Application is different than Invent UI and includes store managers, additional applications are required. The setup steps for using the application are still valid.

However, for the mapping of Phantom Stock users to store IDs, this (user → store_id) additional information is needed.

- Integration with any SAML 2.0 identity provider.
- Forced vs Optional (w/ disabled, optional or mandatory MFA) SSO

Customers have the choice to force all their users to use SSO or it can be just optional. If they choose the forced method;

- Users won’t be able to login with their passwords.

If they choose the optional method;

- Users will be able to login with both password and SSO

Why to use SSO?

- Account management and Security

will be able to login with both password and SSO

Why to use SSO?

- Account management and Security

Customers will be able to manage their own users. When a store manager leaves, the customer will automatically disable their access to the store data. Similarly, when a new manager joins or there is a change in the store manager, customers won't need to remind Invent about the changes.

- Client will respond with the following metadata:User Role: Corporate User, Regional Manager, District Manager, Store ManagerScope Identifiers: For regional managers a list of region IDsFor District Managers a list of District IDsFor Store Managers a list of Store IDsFor Corporate Users, no Scope ID needed

## React Query is not a data fetching library

React Query is an async promise-based state manager. Manages server state and caches the data.

- Server owned: What we see is only a snapshot (which can be outdated).
- Owned by many users: Multiple users could change the data.
- Persisted remotely: It exists across browsing sessions.
- Asynchronous: It takes a bit of time for the data to go from the server to the client.

## Important Concepts

### 1. Deduplication

Deduplicates identical requests to prevent multiple identical requests from being sent. Under the hood, the reason this works is thanks to a well-known software design pattern called Query Observer and Observer Pattern. Only updates when cache changes.

Server State is alive !! In React Query terms, stale is the opposite of fresh. As long as a query is considered fresh, data will only be delivered from the cache. And staleTime is what defines the time (in milliseconds) until a query is considered stale. The default `staleTime` in React Query might surprise you—it's `0`.

Yes, zero milliseconds, meaning every query is instantly considered stale. The documentation calls this "aggressive but sane defaults."

- Aggressive: Queries are refetched more often than necessary.
- Sane: It's better to fetch too often than too little, as stale data can lead to inconsistencies.

This is similar to React re-renders. While we aim to minimize re-renders, too many re-renders are better than too few, as they ensure the UI stays in sync with the state.

The truth is, there isn't a universally perfect default—it always depends on your specific use case.

> Note: Important Note: By passing a staleTime of 5000 to useQuery, we tell React Query to not make the query stale until the data is older than 5 seconds.

```typescript
useQuery({
  queryKey: ["repos", { sort }],
  queryFn: () => fetchRepos(sort),
  staleTime: 5 * 1000 // 5,000 ms or 5 seconds
});
```

What Happens When a Query Becomes Stale?

Naturally, this brings up another question: What happens when a query does become stale?

The answer, once again, might be surprising: nothing.

A stale query doesn't trigger an immediate refetch. Instead, it simply tells React Query that the cached data is considered outdated and can be updated in the background when appropriate.

To better understand this, consider these two scenarios:

pdated in the background when appropriate.

To better understand this, consider these two scenarios:

1. When isStale is false:The query is considered fresh.No background refetch occurs, and the data in the cache is used as-is.
2. When isStale is true:The query is considered stale.React Query may refetch the data in the background, typically when the query is accessed or if triggered by specific events (e.g., window focus or network reconnect).

> Note: Important Note: The transition to a stale state doesn’t mean an immediate fetch but allows React Query to handle cache updates efficiently when necessary. This design helps balance performance and data freshness.

#### Triggers to Refetch Stale Queries

There are four scenarios (or "triggers") when React Query refetches stale queries:

ch Stale Queries

There are four scenarios (or "triggers") when React Query refetches stale queries:

1. The queryKey changesWhen the queryKey changes (e.g., in the example where the sort changes), and the query is stale, React Query refetches the data and updates the cache.
2. A new observer mountsObservers are created by useQuery. When a new component mounts (e.g., a user opens a dialog or navigates to a new screen in an SPA), if the query is stale, React Query refetches the data and updates the cache.
3. The window receives a focus eventReact Query automatically handles this to improve user experience. When the user switches back to the tab running the application, and the query is stale, React Query refetches the data and updates the cache.
4. The device goes onlineAnother user-friendly feature of React Query. If a device reconnects after going offline (e.g., subway users), and the query is stale, React Query refetches the data and updates the cache.

(e.g., subway users), and the query is stale, React Query refetches the data and updates the cache.

> Info: Pro Tip: These default triggers make React Query highly adaptable to real-world scenarios while ensuring data freshness without excessive configuration.

```typescript
//customize the refetching behavior
useQuery({
  queryKey: ["repos", { sort }],
  queryFn: () => fetchRepos(sort),
  refetchOnMount: false,
  refetchOnWindowFocus: false,
  refetchOnReconnect: false,
  staleTime: Infinity // assume the data is always fresh
});
```

#### What Does "Actively Used" Mean?

- Every useQuery call creates an Observer.
- A query with at least one Observer is active.
- A query with no Observers is inactive.

#### How Observers Work

- Observers are created when components using useQuery mount.
- Observers are destroyed when components unmount (and are removed from the DOM).
- If no Observers remain, React Query starts the garbage collection timer.

#### Practical Example: Search Functionality

- Each search term produces a new cache entry.
- When a new search term is used, the previous entry becomes inactive (as the Observer switches to the new queryKey).
- If the same search term is used again within 5 minutes:Data will be served from the cache.A background refetch may occur if the data is stale.

Managing Synchronous Requests Using AWS SQS FIFO Queues

## Background & Need

Some operations within our system require strict sequential processing for requests made to the same endpoint within the same customer scope. This becomes particularly important in cases where we do not use a transactional database. Without proper handling, concurrent requests may lead to data inconsistencies or undesired outcomes. To address this, we need a generic and scalable solution that ensures sequential execution while allowing independent processing for different customer-service-endpoint scopes.

## Problems we want to address

1. User releasing order in exact same time

Imagine user review store replen order. and two different user clicks on same store-sku combination to release it. both of the orders will be exported.

*clarity needs/questions:*

- are we talking about exact time stamp when two users click “release”?

1. Intra Day Supply Calculations

1. Intra Day Supply Calculations

Right now, we have three UI modules that user can edit and release orders for the same SKU-DC combinations. Store Replen + AdHoc Allocation + Manual Order

Risk scenario:

- DC Inventory= 100 in morning batch ETL
- store replen recommended to use 40 units as part of replen run, but it is not auto release so it is waiting in the UI to be approved & released.
- User goes into AdHoc allocation screen (or manual) and create a run and release 100 units of DC inventory at 11am (before replen users did something around that “40”
- When replen users check the UI, they can still release their recommended “40” and in that case we will end up with excess push

*clarity needs/questions:*

*clarity needs/questions:*

- another scenario: in our proposed solution, what will happen when user open the screen at 11.05 and with fresh data at 11.05, they see DC inventory as 40. they stay in the screen for 5 minutes then approve that 40 and release it at 11.10. In Manual order screen, another user login into system at 11.05 and see the “40” again, then release that “40” at 11.09. what will happen in our proposed solution for this case?

## Proposed Queue Solution

We propose leveraging Amazon SQS FIFO queues to enforce message ordering and ensure that requests to the same endpoint within the same customer scope are processed sequentially.
However, a detailed AWS SQS usage analysis is still required, and some aspects of the implementation need further validation. The core idea is:

is still required, and some aspects of the implementation need further validation. The core idea is:

- Each ${client}.${service}.${endpoint} combination maps to a unique Message Group ID.
- Messages within the same group are processed one at a time, ensuring strict ordering.
- Different groups can be processed in parallel, allowing scalability.
- AWS SQS FIFO queues guarantee ordering and prevent message duplication.
- The Queue Message Handler Lambda must be independent of the service to ensure a generic and reusable structure.

### Key AWS SQS FIFO Features Supporting This Approach (Further Validation Required)

From AWS documentation:

- Message Group ID: Used to organize messages into distinct groups. Only one message per group is processed at a time, ensuring strict sequential processing.
- Deduplication: Prevents the same message from being processed multiple times.
- Strict Ordering: Messages are processed in the exact order they are received within a group.

[Reference: AWS SQS FIFO Documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/FIFO-key-terms.html)

### Architecture Overview

The proposed architecture follows these steps:

uide/FIFO-key-terms.html)

### Architecture Overview

The proposed architecture follows these steps:

1. A client makes a synchronous request to Service Lambda.
2. if it is a process that must be handled sequentially,Service Lambda adds the request to a FIFO SQS Queue, using the ${client}.${service}.${endpoint} as the Message Group ID.
3. The FIFO Queue ensures that messages from the same group are processed sequentially.
4. The Queue Message Handler Lambda is triggered for each message from the queue and makes an HTTP call to the appropriate service endpoint, using the path, payload, and auth details from the message.
5. Once the service processes the request, the next message from the same group can be processed.
6. The Queue Message Handler Lambda remains independent from the service, allowing flexible and scalable use across different systems.

## Considerations

### Core Requirements

lowing flexible and scalable use across different systems.

## Considerations

### Core Requirements

- Messages within the same group (${client}.${service}.${endpoint}) must be processed one by one in strict order.
- Messages from different groups should be processed in parallel to maintain system performance.
- No duplicate message processing should occur (each message should be processed exactly once).
- Authentication details must be securely handled throughout the process.The system's auth requirements should be discussed in detail and designed carefully.If using user tokens, token expiration needs to be considered for long-running processes.
- The Queue Message Handler Lambda must be designed as a generic, reusable component that operates independently of the service.
- Consider adding the implementation to cheetah-utils for standardization and reusability.

### Challenges & Open Questions

mplementation to cheetah-utils for standardization and reusability.

### Challenges & Open Questions

- Client Connection & UX Considerations:Many existing endpoints return responses directly, and the frontend expects these responses to display results immediately.When integrating the queue system, responses will no longer be returned synchronously with the original request.This may require a new UX approach for endpoints utilizing this system

Create UserStepsGo to Admin > User Management.
Enter the user’s email—an activation code will be sent.
Select the related customer (e.g., Grocery Demo) and assign a role (e.g., Replenishment Client User).
To add more customer-role pairs, click ‘+’.
Finally, click Create New User.Tip: By default, all Invent Admin roles are assigned to Invent employees.If a specific role is specified, only that role should be assigned.Warning: The Developer role should be assigned only to users who are actual developers.Update & Delete User / Reset PasswordUpdateGo to Admin > User Management, then select Update & Delete User.
Enter the user’s email.
Choose the customer (e.g., Grocery Demo) and assign a role (e.g., Replenishment Client User).
Click ‘+’ to add more customer-role pairs.

emo) and assign a role (e.g., Replenishment Client User).
Click ‘+’ to add more customer-role pairs.
Finish by clicking Add New Role.Info: We can also remove a user’s roles for specific sites, as shown in the example below.Reset PasswordNote: If the user hasn’t logged in and the validation email has expired, click the Reset Password button to send a new email.Note: If the user forgets their password, it can be reset from the login screen.Warning: We typically don’t delete users, but it can be done by clicking Delete button if necessary.

CreateGo to Admin > Default Translations.
Click Add New Translation (top right).
A pop-up will appear.
Use dot notation for keys (e.g., product.parameter.param_name).
Each dot creates a dropdown level; first part is title, last part is the editable key.
Enter the key and its translation value.
Click ‘+’ to add more key-value pairs.

is the editable key.
Enter the key and its translation value.
Click ‘+’ to add more key-value pairs.
Click Add to save.Note: If you don’t use dot notation, the value is treated as a title (e.g., ADMIN, CUB, DEMO).Warning: If there’s a title mistake, it must be deleted from both cheetah.dbo.i18n_key and cheetah.dbo.i18n_translation tables.Edit & DeleteInfo: EditClick the yellow pen icon to edit values.Default translations affect all customers without a customer-specific translation for that key.Info: DeleteWe typically don’t delete default translations, as they might be used in other sections.

This section provides documentation for the backend components and libraries that support the Generative AI (GenAI) functionalities within the Cheetah platform.

## 1. Cheetah Utils Library - GenAI Extensions

This part extends the existing "Cheetah Utils Library" documentation.

#### 1.1. GenAI Filter Parser (gen_ai_filter_parser.js)

- Location: cheetah-backend-cheetah-utils/src/cql/gen_ai_filter_parser.js
- Purpose: This module is responsible for translating an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) into an SQL conditional clause. The AST typically represents a complex filter or query, potentially originating from a GenAI/chatbot interface after natural language processing. This parser allows for dynamic and complex query generation based on structured tree inputs.
- Integration: It's primarily used by the filter_helper.js within the cql module of cheetah-utils when a filter of type: "pattern" is processed.

Key Components:

Key Components:

`specialLookup`Object:

- Purpose: Provides mappings for special identifiers (e.g., CurrentDate, NOW, CURDATE) to generate dynamic SQL values using Knex raw queries, typically for date and time.
- Example Entry:

```
{
  CurrentDate: knexInstance => knexInstance.raw("?", [moment().format("YYYY-MM-DD")])
  // ... other special lookups
}
```

`buildSQLFromAST(node, knex)`Function:

- Purpose: Recursively traverses an input AST node and constructs an SQL string fragment and its corresponding bindings.
- Parameters:node: The AST node object. The function expects specific node.type properties (e.g., Column, Literal, Paren, Add, Div, LastDay, Lower, Upper, comparison operators like lt, eq, etc.).knex: A Knex instance used for generating database-specific raw SQL parts (e.g., for functions like LOWER(), LAST_DAY(), DIV()) and handling bindings correctly.
- Returns: An object: { sql: "SQL_STRING_FRAGMENT", bindings: [value1, value2, ...] }.
- Logic: Handles various AST node types through a switch statement. For binary operations or specific functions, it may call helper functions like buildBinaryOperation or buildDivOperation.
- Error Handling: Throws an error for unknown AST node types.

`buildBinaryOperation(node, operator, knex)`Function:

: Throws an error for unknown AST node types.

`buildBinaryOperation(node, operator, knex)`Function:

- Purpose: Constructs SQL for binary operations (e.g., columnA + ?, fieldX = fieldY).Parameters: node (the AST node containing operands), operator (the SQL operator string like +, =, <), knex.

`buildDivOperation(node, knex)`Function:

- Purpose: Constructs SQL for division operations, potentially using database-specific syntax via knex.raw('div(?,?)', bindings).Parameters: node (the AST node for division), knex.

`isSimpleNode(node)`Function:

- Purpose: A utility to determine if an AST node is "simple" (e.g., a direct literal or column reference) which can influence how bindings are processed, especially in buildDivOperation.

`extractSqlBindings(item)`Function:

ce how bindings are processed, especially in buildDivOperation.

`extractSqlBindings(item)`Function:

- Purpose: Recursively processes the bindings array generated by buildSQLFromAST. It's designed to handle nested structures or Knex raw objects within the bindings to prepare them for final SQL execution.Parameters: item (a single binding or an array/object containing bindings).

#### 1.2. Filter Helper (filter_helper.js) - Pattern Filter Type

- Location: cheetah-backend-cheetah-utils/src/cql/filter_helper.js
- Purpose (in GenAI context): The addFilterToQuery function within this helper is the direct consumer of the gen_ai_filter_parser.js for filters of type: "pattern".
- addFilterToQuery(builder, filter) Function - case "pattern":When filter.filterType is "pattern":It expects filter.filterValues[0] to be the AST object.It calls buildSQLFromAST(ast, builder.client) to get the SQL string and bindings.It calls extractSqlBindings to process the bindings.The resulting SQL and bindings are applied to the query builder using builder.whereRaw(result.sql, result.bindings).Example filter object for a pattern filter:

lder using builder.whereRaw(result.sql, result.bindings).Example filter object for a pattern filter:

{
  "filterName": "complexCondition", // Or any relevant name
  "filterType": "pattern",
  "filterValues": [
    { // This is the AST object
      "type": "eq", // Example AST node
      "this": {"type": "Column", "this": {"this": "revenue"}},
      "expression": {"type": "Literal", "this": 1000}
    }
  ],
  "filterDataType": "patternAst", // Or a similar indicator
  "filterGroup": "some_group_uuid",
  "filterCommon": true
}
```

- Location: cheetah-backend-cheetah-utils/src/cql/index.js
- Purpose (in GenAI context): This module exports the db object which includes addFilters and addRestrictions functions. These functions are the primary entry points for applying filter arrays (which may include "pattern" filters processed by gen_ai_filter_parser.js) to a Knex query builder.
- db.addFilters(builder, filters, filterCommon) & db.addRestrictions(builder, filters):These functions internally use filter_helper.js to apply the filters. If the filters array contains objects with filterType: "pattern", the GenAI parser will be invoked as described above.

# 2. GenAI Proxy Service (cheetah-external-affairs-api/services/gen_ai)

2. GenAI Proxy Service (cheetah-external-affairs-api/services/gen_ai)

- Purpose: This service acts as a backend-for-frontend (BFF) and an intelligent proxy to an external, third-party GenAI API. It simplifies interaction for client applications, handles request/response transformations, enriches requests with necessary metadata and configurations, and manages authentication with the external GenAI provider.
- Key Functionalities:Question Answering to Structured Query: Converts natural language questions (within a specific screen context) into a structured cheetah_request_payload that can be used for data retrieval, or provides a direct textual answer.Image Attribute Extraction: Obtains descriptive attributes for a given image URL.Alert Summarization: Generates summaries for system alerts.
- Source Code Location: cheetah-external-affairs-api/services/gen_ai/
- General Structure: Follows the standard microservice folder structure. (Link to "Backend Documentation - Folder Structure").

ws the standard microservice folder structure. (Link to "Backend Documentation - Folder Structure").

- GEN_AI_API_KEY (Required):Purpose: The path/name in AWS Secrets Manager where the API key for the external GenAI service is stored (e.g., gensight/dev/api).Usage: The services/proxy.ts -> getGenAiApiKey() function retrieves this secret. The secret itself is expected to be a JSON string containing an x-api-key field, e.g., {"x-api-key": "your_actual_api_key"}.
- GARUDA_METADATA_API (Required):Purpose: URL for the cheetah-shu-garuda/services/metadata/ service, used to fetch screen metadata.
- ALERT_API (Required):Purpose: URL for the internal Alert API, used to fetch alert details for summarization.

#### 2.3. Key Utility Functions (services/proxy.ts)

- getGenAiApiKey(): Retrieves API key from AWS Secrets Manager.
- convertKeysToSnakeCase(obj, parentKey): Recursively converts object keys to snake_case for compatibility with the external GenAI API. Skips conversion for keys under a parentKey === "schema".
- arrayToKeyedObject(arr): Transforms an array of {key, value} objects into a single keyed object. Used in requestGenAiSummarization.
- makeGenAiPostRequest(apiPath, payload): Helper function for making authenticated POST requests to the external GenAI API.
- SCREEN_NAME_MAPPING & mapScreenName(screenName): Maps UI screen names to identifiers used by downstream services (like metadata or the GenAI API).

): Maps UI screen names to identifiers used by downstream services (like metadata or the GenAI API).

#### 2.4. External Service Interactions (services/external.ts)

- getScreenMetadata(screenName): Calls POST ${GARUDA_METADATA_API}/screen-metadata.
- fetchAlertDetailsById(alertId): Calls GET ${ALERT_API}/alerts/${alertId}/details.

Below, you will find the steps to create a new page in Cheetah UI.

# 1. Creating the Page Component

- Let’s assume we have a new product called NewFeature and we will create a page for the product named NewFeatureDashboard. First we create a folder named NewFeature under the screens folder and create a file named NewFeatureDashboard.tsx
- Create the NewFeatureDashboard content
- Add NewFeatureDashboard component to the routes.tsx

# 2. Menu Management

Now, when we go to the path /new-feature/dashboard, we expect to see the page we’ve just created. However, we can’t see the page because the app filters routes based on the menu data received from the backend. You can find steps to create a menu item below. A detailed explanation of Menu Item Form can be found [here](https://invent.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/CHEETAH/pages/edit-v2/5300682753#5.-Admin-Menu-Item-Form).

## 2.1 Parent Menu

*(If you do not need to create parent menu item or your parent menu item already exists, you can skip this part.)*

In our case, we create a new product and the product may have several child menu items. So, we will create the parent menu item named NewFeature from Admin > Menu Management > Create Menu Item.

- Enter title, translation key should be used as title.
- Select parent menu, we want our menu to be displayed on the top level so we select “root“.
- Adding a menu item to the root requires to enter a icon name, let’s enter calculator as a icon name.
- Click on Create and parent menu will be created.

## 2.2 Leaf Menu

Now we are ready to add our path as a menu item. Again, we will use the same form to add new menu item.

we are ready to add our path as a menu item. Again, we will use the same form to add new menu item.

- Select under which parent our path will be placed. In our case, New Feature will be the parent
- Mark the menu item as leaf and select the path we’ve just created in 1. Creating Page Component from route select box. Please note that the options in the route select box are populated from the paths defined in the routes.tsx file in the codebase.
- Click on Create and menu item will be created under the selected parent menu item.

## 2.3 Permissions

Since we’ve not assigned any permission to the menu, we cannot see it on navigation menu. We can update menu item permissions on Admin > Menu Management > Menu Dashboard.

- Find the menu item whose permission you want to update, and click the green user icon button.
- From the opened modal, we can assign permissions to the menu item. Only the assigned customer and role will be able to see the menu item.

# 3. Dynamic Paths

We previously mentioned that, for the routes defined in `routes.tsx`, to be visible, they need to be added to the menu in the Admin panel. However, when we want to add pages with dynamic paths (e.g., `/new-feature/detail/:id`), we cannot define each variation individually in the Admin panel. As a result, we cannot access these pages. There are two possible solutions to address this issue:

. As a result, we cannot access these pages. There are two possible solutions to address this issue:

- First solution, Assign the parent value, when defining routes in routes.tsx, to another path that is already defined in the navigation menu. This way, the route becomes accessible by matching with the data received from the backend. Please note that this solution assumes the permissions for the routes are the same.
- Second solution, add menu item for the route just like we did it in 2.2 Leaf Menu. Make the Show field false, so that the menu item will be defined on backend but does not appear in the navigation menu. Also, this solution provides us to manage the menu item’s own permissions.

- Title: This value defines the name displayed in the navigation menu and tabs. You can use translation key as value.

- Is Leaf: This value determines whether a menu item has child route items or not.
- Route: Only selectable if Is Leaf is true. The value represents the path of the menu item. Options are populated from routes.tsx
- Hash: Only visible if selected Route has a tab hash values defined on routes.tsx. The selected hash value is appended to the end of the selected route. Options are populated from selected route item from routes.tsx

ded to the end of the selected route. Options are populated from selected route item from routes.tsx

- Disabled: Determines whether the menu item will be clickable on navigation menu and tabs.

# Cheetah Meetings
Cheetah Meetings
Cheetah Meetings
heetah Meetings
eetah Meetings
etah Meetings
tah Meetings
ah Meetings

- Daily: Mostly core team joins for daily updates. For the first weeks you will join these dailies
- Squad/UX/Cheetos updates: Once a week whole Cheetah meets and we give our weekly updates
- Retrospectives: Once a month we meet to discuss what went well and what can be done better. The comments can be done anonymously. After everyone writes their comments, we go over them one by one. An ice breaker question is asked at the beginning of meeting.
- What is new: New features etc. within Cheetah that is good to share remaining Cheetah members are introduced here. It is done once a month and a file is filled beforehand for the topics of meeting. File is in the meeting invitation.
- Coffee: Once a week we meet to take a break together. This is optional but lets try to join and improve our relation with team.

to take a break together. This is optional but lets try to join and improve our relation with team.
- Cheetah -BE: Biweekly, we backend developer meets to discuss some problems. An excel file is filled before meeting regarding discussion topics. After meeting, which actions are taken is also filled. The excel in meeting invitation.

## Company Meetings

- Omega sprint demos: Once a month new features are introduced and demonstrated if possible within company technical teams
- Monthly meeting: At the end of the month all teams give updates of what did they for the month.

How user onboarding and deprovisioning works in our setup.

- Direct REST API for user management (create/modify/disable): Not available.
- Automation is handled through SSO. We are using AWS Cognito as our identity layer, integrated with your Identity Provider (IdP) via SAML 2.0.

### How it works (Cognito + SAML)

- Onboarding (Create): When you assign the application to a user in your IdP, and the user logs in for the first time, AWS Cognito performs Just-in-Time (JIT) provisioning. The user is automatically created in invent.ai with the attributes provided in the SAML assertion.
- Update (Modify): At each login, attributes are refreshed from the IdP.
- Deprovision (Disable): When you remove the user’s assignment or disable them in your IdP, they can no longer log in. Existing sessions expire based on the configured session TTL.

### Attribute Mapping in SAML

log in. Existing sessions expire based on the configured session TTL.

### Attribute Mapping in SAML

We keep attribute mapping minimal to simplify integration. The IdP sends the following attributes in the SAML assertion:

- Email → Primary user identifier in invent.ai
- Roles → Defines the user’s role in the application (e.g., IA_Admin, IA_Analyst, IA_Viewer)

At login, Cognito reads these attributes and ensures the user profile in [invent.ai](http://invent.ai) is created/updated accordingly.

### About SCIM

AWS Cognito does not provide native SCIM endpoints. While it is technically possible to build a SCIM bridge with AWS Lambda and API Gateway, our current setup is based only on SAML + JIT provisioning.

### Next Steps

This setup allows:

- Automatic user creation at first login
- Role and profile updates at every login
- Access removal when the user is disabled or unassigned in your IdP

## Folder Structure

We should start by creating a folder named features to put react query related code in. We can create subfolders for each feature. Let’s say our feature name is ClusterMatrix. In its subfolder, these files can exist:

```
features/
  ClusterMatrix/
    - clusterMatrix.services.ts
    - clusterMatrix.queries.ts
    - clusterMatrix.query.hooks.ts
    - clusterMatrix.mutations.ts
```

### Services File:

Services file contains the functions that we will use as our query or mutation functions. They can do anything as long as they return a Promise. If a function will fetch data, it should use `typedFetchAPI` for it. You can set the return type like this:

```typescript
export const fetchClusterList = async () => {
  return typedFetchAPI.get<ICluster[]>(ASSORTMENT_API_NAME, "assortment-planning-filters/cluster-list");
};
```

The `staleTime` option determines the amount of time a query's data is considered fresh. While the data is fresh, no background refetch will occur when a new instance of the component mounts. The default `staleTime` is `0`, which means the data is always stale and will refetch in the background on mount. Setting it to `Infinity` makes the data persistently fresh.

The `select` option is a synchronous function that transforms or "selects" a part of the data after the query has successfully fetched it. This is useful for reshaping the data to a more convenient format or for performance optimizations, as the component will only re-render when the selected data changes. The `select` function runs every time the data changes.

You can find example usages for them in our codebase under assortment project.

### Mutations File

In React Query, [mutations](https://tanstack.com/query/latest/docs/framework/react/guides/mutations)are used for any asynchronous server-side operations that change data, such as creating, updating, or deleting resources. Unlike queries which are concerned with data fetching, mutations are all about modifying data on the server.

The [useMutation](https://tanstack.com/query/latest/docs/framework/react/reference/useMutation) hook is what you use to manage these mutations in your React components. It returns an object that contains the mutation function itself and all the information about the mutation's state.

`mutationFn` is the required option of useMutation. It can be a function that you defined in `<featureName>.services.ts` file.

  postProductWithFilters: () => [...newSeasonPanelMutationKeys.postProduct(), "with-filters"]
};
```

This guide helps developers use Cursor AI effectively in their daily work. The core principle: You must understand every line of code you commit. AI is a tool for productivity, not a replacement for engineering judgment.

This guide is for humans - it teaches you how to interact with Cursor AI to maintain code quality and consistency.

## 1. Core Workflow

### The Golden Rule

```
Analyze → Plan → Implement → Test → Review → Commit
```

### Daily Development Process

#### Starting a New Task

Step 1: Give Cursor the context Tell Cursor about your task:

```
"I'm working on [JIRA-XXX]: [description]
First, check package.json to understand the project setup.
Then analyze the existing codebase to understand:
- How similar features are implemented
- What patterns are being used
- Error handling approach
- Testing patterns"
```

Step 2: Request a plan Ask Cursor to create a plan:

```
"Based on existing patterns, create an implementation plan"
```

Step 3: Review the plan before approving

d on existing patterns, create an implementation plan"
```

Step 3: Review the plan before approving

- Check if the plan follows existing patterns
- Verify it doesn't introduce unnecessary complexity
- Ensure all edge cases are covered
- Confirm the approach makes sense for your requirements
- If something looks wrong, ask Cursor to revise before proceeding

## 2. Pattern-First Development

### ✅ What Developers Should Always Do

Start by asking Cursor to analyze patterns:

```
"Analyze the existing codebase and show me:
1. Project structure
2. Naming conventions
3. Error handling patterns
4. Testing approach
5. Code style
6. Common utilities
7. Third-party libraries"
```

### ❌ What to Avoid

- Create new patterns when existing ones work
- Add dependencies without checking existing ones
- Skip testing
- Commit code you don't understand
- Allow bulk refactoring without approval

## 3. Quick Developer Checklist

| --- | --- |

| Tests missing | Request tests with implementation |
| Hardcoded values | Check for existing config approach |

## 7. Integration with .cursorrules

### What is .cursorrules?

A configuration file that tells Cursor how to behave for your specific project.

### How to Set Up

A configuration file that tells Cursor how to behave for your specific project.

### How to Set Up

### If Something Breaks in Production

## 8. Emergency Protocols

### If Something Breaks in Production

1. Don't panic
2. Don't use Cursor to fix production directly
3. Reproduce locally
4. Test fix thoroughly
5. Deploy with rollback plan

### Red Flags - Stop and Review

- 🚨 Deleting multiple files
- 🚨 Major refactoring (>200 lines)
- 🚨 Changing auth logic
- 🚨 Modifying database schemas
- 🚨 Adding new dependencies
- 🚨 Bypassing security

## 9. Best Practices Summary

### DO's ✅

- Analyze patterns first
- Plan before coding
- Test everything
- Understand every line
- Follow existing conventions
- Keep changes incremental

### DON'Ts ❌

- Skip pattern analysis
- Create unnecessary abstractions
- Mix coding styles
- Ignore existing utilities
- Commit without understanding
- Trust AI blindly

## Overview

This document describes the structure of the Computed Filter Configuration object. This is the final JSON payload sent to the frontend application after the backend has processed the raw database configuration.

The computed config is derived by:

1. Flattening: Merging static, dynamic, and logic-specific fields into a single level.
2. Structuring: Grouping related filters into parent-child hierarchies (specifically for remote select types).
3. Transforming: Converting specific logical types into their final UI representation.

## 1. The Core Object

The configuration is a simple wrapper containing an ordered list of filters.

```
{
  "filters": [ ... ]
}
```

---

## 2. Common Properties

Every filter object in the array, regardless of its type, shares these base properties.

Properties

Every filter object in the array, regardless of its type, shares these base properties.

| Field | Type | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| key | String | Unique Identifier. The database key for the filter (e.g., product_id). Note: Remote Select Groups use filterGroupId instead. |
| label | String | Localization key for the UI label (e.g., GENERAL.PRODUCT). |
| visible | Boolean | true if the filter should be rendered in the UI. |
| required | Boolean | true if the user is forced to select a value. |
| save | Boolean | true if the user's selection should be persisted for next session. |
| filterDataType | String | Hint for data handling (e.g., string, number, date). |
| filterCommon | Boolean | Internal flag for common filter logic. |
| entity | Boolean | String |

---

## 3. Filter Types

The schema uses the `type` field to determine the specific structure.

### A. Leaf Filters (Flat Inputs)

These are standalone inputs with no children.

#### 1. Text / Textarea

. Leaf Filters (Flat Inputs)

These are standalone inputs with no children.

#### 1. Text / Textarea

Used for free-text search or manual input.

- type: "text" or "textarea"
- filterType: The comparison operator to use ("eq", "neq", "cn", "sw", etc.).
- filterTypeSwitch: (Textarea only) Boolean. If true, UI allows toggling between input modes.

#### 2. Date / Date Range

Used for picking single dates or ranges.

- type: "date" or "dateRange"
- default (Date) / defaultStartDate (Range): Defines the initial value.Absolute: { type: "absolute", value: { absoluteType: "startOf", absoluteValue: "year" } }Delta: { type: "delta", value: 1 } (e.g., "1 week ago")

#### 3. Range / Time Slider

Used for selecting numeric ranges (e.g., Forecast values).

- type: "range" or "timeSlider"
- start / end: Object containing { min, max, default } limits.
- secondLabel: (TimeSlider only) Optional label for the secondary axis.

#### 4. Switch

A simple boolean toggle.

: (TimeSlider only) Optional label for the secondary axis.

#### 4. Switch

A simple boolean toggle.

- type: "switch"
- description: Optional text description rendered next to the toggle.

---

### B. Select Filters (Dropdowns)

The `select` type has two distinct forms depending on the `remote` flag.

#### 1. Remote Select (Hierarchy Container)

Used when data comes from the database, often allowing hierarchical drilling (e.g., Region -> Store). This object acts as a Container and is not an input itself.

- type: "select"
- remote: true
- filterGroupId: The ID used to group the child levels together.
- distinct: Boolean. If true, fetches distinct values.
- children: Array of Child Objects defining the hierarchy levels.

Child Object Structure:

t values.
- children: Array of Child Objects defining the hierarchy levels.

Child Object Structure:

> Note: Child objects define the actual inputs inside the group.FieldTypeDescriptionkeyStringUnique key for this level (e.g., h1).multiBooleantrue allows multiple selections.tablesArrayDefinition of database tables/partitions for fetching data.aliasStringSQL Alias for the column query.keyTableStringTable override for the key column.textareaBooleanIf true, this level renders as a text input instead of a dropdown.

#### 2. Local Select (Flat Dropdown)

Used for simple, hardcoded lists (e.g., Status: "Active", "Inactive"). This is a standalone input.

- type: "select"
- remote: false
- key: Unique identifier for the input.
- localFilterOptions: Object containing the hardcoded data.options: Array of { label: "...", value: "..." } objects.default: The default selected value.
- multi: Boolean. If true, allows multiple selections.

---

## 4. Computed vs. Storage Schema Differences

i: Boolean. If true, allows multiple selections.

---

## 4. Computed vs. Storage Schema Differences

If you are working with the backend database, note these transformations:

1. Flattened Structure:Storage: Properties are nested in static (metadata) and dynamic (runtime).Computed: All properties are at the root level (e.g., filter.label instead of filter.static.label).
2. Lifted Properties:Storage: Table definitions are deeply nested in remoteFilterOptions.Computed: tables, alias, and keyTable are direct properties of the Select Child object.
3. No Child Types:Storage: Children are full filter objects.Computed: Children in a Remote Select group do not have type or id properties.

This document defines the expected behavior for permission management across different environments and introduces guardrails to prevent accidental permission assignments to sensitive environments.

*This document may subject to be updated after having decided guardrail feature*

---

## Overview

The Menu Dashboard (`/admin/menu/menu-dashboard`) allows administrators to assign permissions to menu items for different customers and environments. This document establishes guidelines and safety mechanisms to prevent accidental permission grants to production or UAT environments.

---

## Environment Classification

### Environment Types

| Environment | Naming Pattern | Risk Level | Confirmation Required |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Test | Ends with "Test" (e.g., "Academy Test") | Low | No |
| UAT | Ends with "UAT" (e.g., "Academy UAT") | Medium | Yes (Warning) |
| Production | No suffix (e.g., "Academy") | High | Yes (Danger) |

---

## Permission Assignment Guardrails

tion | No suffix (e.g., "Academy") | High | Yes (Danger) |

---

## Permission Assignment Guardrails

### Confirmation Modal Behavior

When assigning permissions to sensitive environments, a confirmation modal should be displayed:

#### UAT Environment Warning

- Color: Warning (Amber/Yellow)
- Icon: Warning triangle
- Title: "UAT Environment Permission"
- Message: "You are about to grant permissions to a UAT environment. This environment is used for user acceptance testing and may be visible to stakeholders."

#### Production Environment Warning

- Color: Danger (Red)
- Icon: Alert/Exclamation
- Title: "Production Environment Permission"
- Message: "You are about to grant permissions to a PRODUCTION environment. This will immediately affect live users. Please ensure the feature is fully tested and approved."

### Modal Requirements

affect live users. Please ensure the feature is fully tested and approved."

### Modal Requirements

1. Cancel Button: Always visible, primary action for safety
2. Confirm Button: Requires explicit click, not pre-selected
3. Environment Badge: Display the detected environment type
4. Customer Name: Show the full customer name being affected

*The Modal guardrail may subject to change due to UI/UX decisions.*

---

## Incident Prevention Best Practices

### Common Mistakes to Avoid

1. No visual distinction: All environments look the same in the UI
2. No confirmation step: Permissions granted with a single click
3. Wrong customer selected: Easy to select wrong customer from dropdown

### Prevention Measures

1. Visual Indicators: Color-coded environment badges help identify risk
2. Confirmation Modals: Required step for UAT/Production grants
3. Checklist Documentation: Reference this document before granting permissions
4. Team Awareness: Share this guide with all team members who manage permissions

## Overview

The Translation Pages feature provides administrative interfaces for managing internationalization (i18n) translations within the Cheetah UI application. It consists of two main screens:

1. Default Translations (/admin/default-translations) - System-wide translation management for base language labels
2. Customer Translations (/admin/customer-translations) - Customer-specific translation overrides

Both screens share common components but operate on different API endpoints and serve distinct purposes.

## Data Model

### Translation Key Structure

Translation keys follow a hierarchical dot-notation format:

```
{PARENT_PREFIX}.{SUB_PREFIX}.{TRANSLATION_KEY}
```

Examples:

- ADMIN.USERS.PAGE_TITLE - Admin section, Users subsection
- GENERAL.SAVE - General section, no subsection
- GENAI.SYNONYM.PRODUCT.BRAND - GenAI section, Synonym > Product hierarchy

slationHierarchy

Purpose: Extracts hierarchical prefixes from translation keys

Exported Functions:

| Hook | Returns | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| useTranslationPrefixes | ITranslationPrefix[] | Extracts parent prefixes for tabs |

### useTranslationValidation

Purpose: Comprehensive validation for translation inputs

Validation Rules:

| Validation | Rule |
| --- | --- |
| Translation Key | No dots (.) or spaces allowed |
| Parent Prefix | Letters only, no special characters |
| Sub Prefix | Maximum 2 levels (e.g., PARENT.CHILD) |
| Uniqueness | No duplicate sub-prefixes within same parent |
| Hierarchy Conflicts | Same segment cannot appear at different hierarchy levels |

Example Hierarchy Conflict:

Conflicts | Same segment cannot appear at different hierarchy levels |

Example Hierarchy Conflict:

```
// Allowed (same position):
TEST.PARENT.CHILD.key1
TEST.PARENT.CHILD.key2

// Blocked (different positions):
TEST.PARENT.CHILD.key1
TEST.CHILD.key2  // CHILD appears at different levels - BLOCKED
```

## State Management

### React Query (Primary)

Server state is managed through React Query for:

- Data fetching with caching
- Optimistic updates
- Background refetching
- Query invalidation on mutations

### Local Component State

UI state managed with React hooks:

- selectedTab - Current active tab
- selectedQuickFilter - Active filter selection
- editedCellsState - Tracked cell changes for batch save
- hasUnsavedChanges - Unsaved changes flag (via ref)

### Redux (Legacy)

cell changes for batch save
- hasUnsavedChanges - Unsaved changes flag (via ref)

### Redux (Legacy)

The `translationsSlice.ts` exists for legacy purposes:

- Stores login-related translations
- Pre-authentication i18n data
- Not actively used in Translation Pages screens

## User Workflows

### Editing Translations

1. User navigates to Default/Customer Translations page
2. Data loads via React Query
3. User selects tab (parent prefix)
4. Optionally applies quick filter
5. Edits cell values inline (DataTable)
6. Unsaved changes flag activates
7. User clicks "Save" to persist
8. Query invalidates and refetches

### Adding New Translations (Default Only)

cks "Save" to persist
8. Query invalidates and refetches

### Adding New Translations (Default Only)

1. User clicks "Add New Translations"
2. Modal opens with empty row
3. User selects/enters parent prefix
4. User selects/enters sub-prefix (optional)
5. User enters translation key
6. User enters English label
7. Optionally adds more rows via + button
8. User clicks "Add" to create
9. Validation runs on submission
10. On success, modal closes and data refreshes

### Preventing Data Loss

The system prevents accidental data loss:

- Tab changes blocked with unsaved changes
- Filter changes blocked with unsaved changes
- Warning message displayed to user
- User must save or refresh to proceed

## Role Hierarchy (from least to most privileged)

The roles are intentionally ordered from lowest to highest level of access to clearly reflect authorization boundaries:

1. Report UserRead-only access.Can view reports and outputs.No configuration, no data modification, and no access to operational pages.
2. Client UserStandard operational user.Can interact with screens and workflows assigned to the product.No administrative or configuration permissions.Has access to assigned client-level pages according to granted permissions (read or limited actions).
3. Client AdminAdministrative role on the client side.Can manage client-level users, and settings.Cannot access Invent-level (internal) features.
4. Invent AdminHighest level of access.Full administrative control, including internal Invent features.Can configure, manage, and troubleshoot the product end-to-end.

This hierarchy is consistent across all products to ensure predictable and controlled access management.
